SIMPLE: equestrian
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Equestrian
<hw>E*ques"tri*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>equester</ets>, from <ets>eques</ets> horseman, fr.
<ets>equus</ets> horse: cf. F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧questre</ets>. See
<er>Equine</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to horses or
horsemen, or to horsemanship; <as>as, <ex>equestrian</ex> feats, or
games</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Being or riding on horseback; mounted; <as>as, an
<ex>equestrian</ex> statue</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An <qex>equestrian</qex> lady appeared upon the plains.</q>
<rj><qau>Spectator.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Belonging to, or composed of, the ancient Roman
<xex>equities</xex> or knights; <as>as, the <ex>equestrian</ex>
order</as>.</def> <rj><au>Burke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Equestrian</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Equestrian
<hw>E*ques"tri*an</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who rides on horseback; a
horseman; a rider.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Equestrianism</ent>⟦br⟧
